*The* art of carpet weaving was particularly significant in the Ottoman Empire carpets having an immense importance both as decorative furnishings rich in religious and other symbolism and as a practical consideration as it was customary to remove one's shoes in living quarters The weaving of such carpets originated in the nomadic cultures of central Asia (carpets being an easily transportable form of furnishing), and was eventually spread to the settled societies of Anatolia.
